column16: After dinner in Surprise Arizona, I went out to my Hertz rental car in the restaurant parking lot and it would not start. I called Hertz roadside assistance to arrange for a new car. I was put on hold. Hertz roadside assistance came back on and informed me that because no one at the Phoenix Airport Hertz location would answer the phone, she could not arrange for replacement car and I would need to ride in the tow truck back to the Phoenix Hertz and arrange for a replacement myself. I reluctantly agreed because I was not given any other choice. The Roadside assistance person started talking about a double tow without explaining what that means. While waiting for the tow truck to arrive. I attempted several times to call the Phoenix airport Hertz office, but was unable. I call another business at the airport that had a direct number to Hertz and called that. I was told that Hertz would not be able to deliver a replacement car to me because a tow truck was already dispatched. I found this unacceptable as I was not in a hurry and could wait. But was again told that it was not possible. After requesting a manager, I was offered to have a replacement sent to my hotel later that evening and after the original car was returned by the towing company. I walked from the restaurant back to my hotel to wait. (this is in the Phoenix area. It was 107 degrees) A replacement car was delivered a few hours later. After checking my cell phone logs, I added up the time I spent on the phone with Hertz-trying to get someone to answer, talking to a representative, or on hold - 67 minutes. 67 minutes to get Hertz to agree to send a replacement for one of your cars that broke down it POOR customer service. I my current job, I rent cars often and make the choice of companies myself. I will definitely be considering choices other than Hertz.

column16: It has been a long time since my last car rental with Hertz. I was very pleased with being able to choose among a number of different vehicles within the class. The only difficulty was with the shuttle returning to the airport after dropping off the car. I assumed that all shuttles would stop at each terminal. However, the shuttle bypassed Terminal 3 (the terminal I needed) and went straight on to Terminal 4. My Wife and I had to take the skytrain to get to Terminal 3. Fortunately, we had more than sufficient time to make our flight, but the added effort of moving our luggage up and down escalators etc. was a bit burdensome. RECOMMENDATION: Provide better identification/signs for which shuttles go to which terminal(s). Other than the minor shuttle experience, I was very pleased with my car rental experience with Hertz.

Having been a Gold Member for over 10 years, I have never felt the need to comment negatively. I've always been very pleased with every aspect of Hertz Gold Member service. However, on my latest rental receipt, I saw on my bill that I was charged for satellite radio at $4.99 per day. As a Gold Member, I pick any car in the Gold area. I don't know whether it has satellite radio or not, especially since most vehicles have a satellite radio button. How am I supposed to know if it's active? Sadly, this seems a little scammy to me. Put a car on the Gold lot, have a Gold member select it, hope the member doesn't look at their receipt, and voila, an extra $4.99 a day to the profit center. Personally, I have satellite radio on all my cars. And, I know most vehicle manufacturers offer the option free for the first 1 to 2 years of ownership, depending on the manufacturer. In reviewing the Hertz website, it is clearly stated that Sirius radio is an extra cost. However, for Gold Members who pick any car on the Gold lot and don't know whether a car has the option, please don't charge us. OR, put a BIG sign in the window stating: "This vehicle includes satellite radio - choosing this vehicle will result in an additional $4.99 per day fee.

I had a reservation to pick up a Class C vehicle from Hertz near Sky Harbor Airport after a flight into Phoenix. When I arrived, I was informed by the woman working the desk that I could go downstairs to the parking garage and pick any car in the Gold lot. When I got down to the lot, not only were there no cars in the Gold lot, there were no cars in any section of the lot! The employee made no mention of this! We stood there wondering what to do and searched around the parking garage for an employee but it was a ghost town with no one there readily available to assist customers. Eventually, another customer who was waiting for a vehicle told us that we would have to hurry and grab any car we saw pull in because there were not enough cars for the amount of people waiting. Cars were arriving so infrequently that customers were sprinting with their luggage to the vehicles in order to get to the car first. My husband and I stood there waiting for half an hour until a Toyota Corolla was dropped off which we were forced to take because we were in a time crunch. So not only did we have to wait outside in the 100 degree Phoenix heat with all of our luggage for a half an hour, but we were not even able to receive the Class C car that we had made a reservation and paid for. This was my first time renting with Hertz and I learned my lesson. In the future I will be sticking with Enterprise.
